who lacks an immune system.

253
00:09:39,830 --> 00:09:41,312
Edwards?

254
00:09:41,381 --> 00:09:42,892
I was on her service yesterday.
She's not doing anything.

255
00:09:42,916 --> 00:09:44,293
She's just staring at
a computer screen.

256
00:09:44,317 --> 00:09:46,401
That is not nothing.
She's thinking.

257
00:09:46,469 --> 00:09:47,918
Her brain is turning,

258
00:09:47,987 --> 00:09:50,238
building up to that
moment of inspiration.

259
00:09:50,306 --> 00:09:54,442
It'll look like nothing, but in a
moment... Pow! The Fourth of July.

260
00:09:54,511 --> 00:09:56,928
Don't blink. You'll miss it.

261
00:09:58,898 --> 00:10:01,677
It was like that with me
and Yang at first, too.

262
00:10:01,701 --> 00:10:05,221
A lot of staring at computer
screens, and now look at us.

263
00:10:05,489 --> 00:10:07,054
Oh, Shane.

264
00:10:08,074 --> 00:10:09,657
Oh, Shane, Shane, Shane.

265
00:10:09,726 --> 00:10:10,925
No.

266
00:10:10,993 --> 00:10:12,793
I wasn't gonna do
this to you today.

267
00:10:12,862 --> 00:10:14,307
I really wasn't. Was I, ladies?

268
00:10:14,331 --> 00:10:15,741
She wasn't. Hand to God.

269
00:10:15,765 --> 00:10:17,243
But you just got too
big for your britches.

270
00:10:17,267 --> 00:10:18,845
It's not even interesting stuff.

271
00:10:18,869 --> 00:10:20,379
I'm just in the printing lab
making sample conduits.

272
00:10:20,403 --> 00:10:22,670
Well, not anymore, swap monkey!

273
00:10:22,738 --> 00:10:25,256
Enjoy working with Dr. Bailey.

274
00:10:25,325 --> 00:10:26,958
Pow! Fourth of July!

275
00:10:28,295 --> 00:10:30,415
Sucks. Swap monkey!

276
00:10:30,463 --> 00:10:31,729
Okay, guys, bear with me.

277
00:10:31,798 --> 00:10:33,342
I know we've gone
through all this before,

278
00:10:33,366 --> 00:10:35,444
but the hospital just needs
your consent one more time.

279
00:10:35,468 --> 00:10:37,668
Go ahead, Murphy.
State your name.

280
00:10:37,737 --> 00:10:39,204
Keith Kalber.

281
00:10:39,272 --> 00:10:40,917
Keith, you understand that
the kidney you're getting today

282
00:10:40,941 --> 00:10:43,886
is being donated from a
person infected with HIV?

283
00:10:43,910 --> 00:10:45,377
I should hope so.

284
00:10:45,445 --> 00:10:47,423
I was there the day
he got his diagnosis.

285
00:10:47,447 --> 00:10:50,226
And although small, there
is a risk of superinfection

286
00:10:50,250 --> 00:10:52,851
by mixing his strain
of the virus with yours.

287
00:10:52,919 --> 00:10:54,936
Knowing this, do you
still wish to proceed?

288
00:10:55,004 --> 00:10:56,370
I do.

289
00:10:56,439 --> 00:10:59,006
God, it feels like
we're getting married.

290
00:10:59,075 --> 00:11:00,686
How would you
know how that feels?

291
00:11:00,710 --> 00:11:02,243
Excuse me?

292
00:11:02,311 --> 00:11:04,863
He always has the best
boyfriends, but he refuses to commit.

293
00:11:04,931 --> 00:11:08,766
Can we just get back
to my huge sacrifice?

294
00:11:08,835 --> 00:11:10,647
Marty, you understand

295
00:11:10,671 --> 00:11:13,171
that the risks of donation
are similar to those involved

296
00:11:13,239 --> 00:11:16,474
with any major surgery, such
as bleeding and infection?

297
00:11:16,542 --> 00:11:18,087
And death resulting
from kidney donation

298
00:11:18,111 --> 00:11:19,351
is extremely rare.

299
00:11:20,580 --> 00:11:22,496
Define "extremely."

300
00:11:23,333 --> 00:11:25,066
.06%.

301
00:11:27,103 --> 00:11:28,269
Um...

302
00:11:31,191 --> 00:11:33,024
We've beaten worse odds.

303
00:11:33,093 --> 00:11:34,192
Oh, yeah.

304
00:11:40,099 --> 00:11:41,928
Now, before we drill
into someone's brain,

305
00:11:41,952 --> 00:11:44,530
we need to make sure they're
good candidates for robotics work.

306
00:11:44,554 --> 00:11:46,999
They need to be motivated,
stable, and neurologically healthy.

307
00:11:47,023 --> 00:11:49,101
This machine gives
us a window into all that.

308
00:11:49,125 --> 00:11:50,636
Hmm-mmm. Yeah, you're
gonna be our baseline.

309
00:11:50,660 --> 00:11:52,304
So, we're just gonna
show you some pictures,

310
00:11:52,328 --> 00:11:54,568
and all you need
to do is look at them.

311
00:12:00,403 --> 00:12:01,853
Okay, Wilson, you ready?

312
00:12:05,992 --> 00:12:07,691
That's the amygdala, right?

313
00:12:07,761 --> 00:12:09,760
It's fired up by powerful
negative emotions,

314
00:12:09,829 --> 00:12:11,440
like fear, rage,
anger, and hate.

315
00:12:11,464 --> 00:12:15,366
Okay, now let's take a look
at her nucleus accumbens.

316
00:12:15,435 --> 00:12:17,595
Her pleasure center? Hmm-mmm.

317
00:12:21,024 --> 00:12:23,291
That's not supposed to happen.

318
00:12:23,360 --> 00:12:25,287
Wilson, what's wrong with
you? You don't like cats?

319
00:12:25,311 --> 00:12:26,527
Hate 'em.

320
00:12:31,801 --> 00:12:33,651
What's wrong with the beach?

321
00:12:33,719 --> 00:12:36,737
<i>Sand in my eyes, skin cancer,
vacations I never got to take as a child.</i>

322
00:12:36,806 --> 00:12:39,857
Uh-oh. Open comminuted
radius fracture in the ER.

323
00:12:39,926 --> 00:12:41,276
There we go. Look at that.

324
00:12:41,344 --> 00:12:43,889
Took a broken arm
to make her happy.

325
00:12:43,913 --> 00:12:46,414
I turned her on to ortho a
few weeks ago. Watch this.

326
00:12:46,483 --> 00:12:48,799
Hey, Wilson, you want to
go set that arm yourself?

327
00:12:50,337 --> 00:12:51,552
I love our new toy.

328
00:12:59,262 --> 00:13:02,664
Yang get too fancy for you, kicked
you down here to the "B" team?

329
00:13:02,732 --> 00:13:05,500
Oh, no. I wanted to see
the work you're doing.

330
00:13:07,303 --> 00:13:10,154
Genome sequencing
is the future of medicine.

331
00:13:10,222 --> 00:13:13,224
May not be a fancy surgery,
but it's gonna save lives.

332
00:13:13,293 --> 00:13:16,744
You want to save lives, or
go to fancy award dinners?

333
00:13:16,812 --> 00:13:18,732
Save lives. Don't get me wrong.

334
00:13:18,765 --> 00:13:21,365
I'm happy for Dr. Yang.
Why wouldn't I be?

335
00:13:21,434 --> 00:13:24,168
I trained her, molded her.

336
00:13:24,237 --> 00:13:25,837
It's almost like it's
my nomination, too.

337
00:13:26,940 --> 00:13:28,183
Keith and Marty are good to go.

338
00:13:28,207 --> 00:13:31,358
Yes. Your high-profile
kidney transplant.

339
00:13:31,428 --> 00:13:32,872
I thought you were
harvesting the donor.

340
00:13:32,896 --> 00:13:34,306
Yeah, while you do
the award-winning stuff.

341
00:13:34,330 --> 00:13:36,163
Yeah, I remember.

342
00:13:36,232 --> 00:13:37,982
Page me when you're ready.

343
00:13:39,853 --> 00:13:40,996
Trained her, too.

344
00:13:41,020 --> 00:13:43,387
Thank you so much
for getting back to me.

345
00:13:43,456 --> 00:13:46,991
I hear you're developing a
drug-eluting cardiac pump

346
00:13:47,060 --> 00:13:49,127
that's getting excellent
results in sheep.

347
00:13:50,363 --> 00:13:52,430
Yes, that's me.

348
00:13:52,498 --> 00:13:54,658
Well, there are four
other excellent surgeons

349
00:13:54,701 --> 00:13:57,635
who are nominated. Thank you.

350
00:13:57,704 --> 00:14:00,238
Yes. Anyway, I
have a young patient.

351
00:14:00,307 --> 00:14:02,340
He's on day 10 of ECMO

352
00:14:02,408 --> 00:14:04,792
and has a protein S deficiency.

353
00:14:06,095 --> 00:14:07,261
Sorry?

354
00:14:08,798 --> 00:14:12,467
I'm 3D printing conduits
for HLHS patients.

355
00:14:12,535 --> 00:14:14,368
Yeah.

356
00:14:14,437 --> 00:14:16,649
Well, I think my patient would
be an excellent candidate

357
00:14:16,673 --> 00:14:18,172
for a compassionate release.

358
00:14:19,141 --> 00:14:21,809
In here. I see.

359
00:14:21,877 --> 00:14:23,745
Oh, God. Oh, no, no, no. What?

360
00:14:23,813 --> 00:14:25,290
The little boy's ECMO
circuit clotted off,

361
00:14:25,314 --> 00:14:27,298
and he's not
responding to fluids.

362
00:14:27,367 --> 00:14:29,717
Page Dr. Hunt and Dr. Robbins.

363
00:14:29,786 --> 00:14:31,063
Okay, let's get
him off that bed...

364
00:14:31,087 --> 00:14:32,986
<i>Dr. Yang?</i>

365
00:14:33,055 --> 00:14:35,423
<i>Dr. Yang, is
everything all right?</i>

366
00:14:35,491 --> 00:14:36,957
<i>Dr. Yang? Hello?</i>

367
00:14:39,261 --> 00:14:40,794
She can't talk right now.

368
00:14:51,274 --> 00:14:53,508
He's clotting, even
on the heparin.

369
00:14:53,576 --> 00:14:54,987
I can't give him any
more or he'll bleed out,

370
00:14:55,011 --> 00:14:57,878
and I can't give him any
less or he'll keep clotting.

371
00:14:57,947 --> 00:15:00,431
We need the
Stanford artificial heart.

372
00:15:00,499 --> 00:15:01,593
We can't have it.

373
00:15:01,617 --> 00:15:02,934
What?

374
00:15:03,002 --> 00:15:05,203
It's not them. They
want to let us try.

375
00:15:05,271 --> 00:15:07,371
It's the FDA.

376
00:15:07,440 --> 00:15:10,641
They're being conservative and
insisting on one more animal trial.

377
00:15:10,710 --> 00:15:12,409
They're six months
away from approval.

378
00:15:12,478 --> 00:15:13,978
Okay, so what do we do?

379
00:15:14,047 --> 00:15:15,696
We hope UNOS calls.

380
00:15:16,899 --> 00:15:18,566
Today.

381
00:15:18,635 --> 00:15:19,635
Yeah.

382
00:15:29,629 --> 00:15:33,397
Okay, time to get you
prepped and ready for...

383
00:15:35,502 --> 00:15:36,834
I can't do it.

384
00:15:37,403 --> 00:15:39,504
Keith's right.

385
00:15:39,572 --> 00:15:42,439
I mean, we've beaten huge odds.

386
00:15:42,508 --> 00:15:46,978
We're still alive while so
many of our friends died.

387
00:15:47,046 --> 00:15:50,564
And I've been healthy
for so long now.

388
00:15:50,633 --> 00:15:53,150
You get a little cocky.

389
00:15:53,219 --> 00:15:55,986
You forget how lucky you are.

390
00:15:56,055 --> 00:15:57,688
And I...

391
00:15:57,741 --> 00:16:00,574
I'm the most horrible
friend, but I just...

392
00:16:01,277 --> 00:16:02,459
I'm scared.

393
00:16:03,363 --> 00:16:08,166
What if I'm one of the .06%?

394
00:16:08,234 --> 00:16:10,935
I don't think I can
give him my kidney.

395
00:16:12,739 --> 00:16:14,738
Have you told Keith?

396
00:16:16,425 --> 00:16:18,826
He's been suffering for so long,

397
00:16:18,895 --> 00:16:21,763
and when the law was
passed, he was so happy.

398
00:16:21,831 --> 00:16:24,899
And then I turned out
to be a perfect match.

399
00:16:25,468 --> 00:16:27,134
And now...

400
00:16:27,203 --> 00:16:29,836
How can I look my
best friend in the eye

401
00:16:29,905 --> 00:16:32,506
and tell him I
won't save his life?

402
00:16:38,214 --> 00:16:41,548
It is unfortunate,
but it does happen.

403
00:16:41,617 --> 00:16:44,385
We misread the
screening, and it turns out

404
00:16:44,453 --> 00:16:47,755
that Marty is not
a suitable donor.

405
00:16:49,559 --> 00:16:51,258
I don't understand.

406
00:16:51,327 --> 00:16:53,494
Yeah, this is outrageous.

407
00:16:53,563 --> 00:16:55,813
I'm completely shocked.

408
00:16:55,882 --> 00:16:57,214
So were we.

409
00:16:57,283 --> 00:16:59,650
Shocked and disappointed.

410
00:16:59,719 --> 00:17:01,218
So, what now?

411
00:17:01,287 --> 00:17:03,371
Well, you'll
continue on dialysis

412
00:17:03,439 --> 00:17:05,473
and go back on
the transplant list.

413
00:17:07,844 --> 00:17:10,210
You know, it's ironic.

414
00:17:11,030 --> 00:17:14,131
I spend years fighting HIV.

415
00:17:14,200 --> 00:17:15,732
I get myself to the point

416
00:17:15,801 --> 00:17:18,820
where the virus is virtually
nonexistent in my body.

417
00:17:19,422 --> 00:17:21,955
I survive.

418
00:17:22,024 --> 00:17:24,035
And now I die of kidney disease.

419
00:17:24,059 --> 00:17:27,895
I'm so sorry. I'm so, so sorry.

420
00:17:27,963 --> 00:17:30,531
It's not your fault. You tried.

421
00:17:30,599 --> 00:17:32,767
You stepped up.

422
00:17:32,835 --> 00:17:34,201
Oh, God.

423
00:17:34,287 --> 00:17:36,553
I don't know what I
would do without you.

424
00:17:42,161 --> 00:17:43,795
What do you do for a living?

425
00:17:43,863 --> 00:17:45,213
<i>I'm an orthopedic surgeon.</i>

426
00:17:47,734 --> 00:17:49,761
Do you enjoy
your work? I love it.

427
00:17:49,785 --> 00:17:51,230
<i>Are you married?</i> Yep.

428
00:17:51,254 --> 00:17:53,687
<i>Any kids?</i> One.

429
00:17:53,756 --> 00:17:56,023
Would you consider
yourself a happy person?

430
00:17:56,091 --> 00:17:57,291
Extremely.

431
00:17:57,360 --> 00:17:59,104
<i>And you want to
participate in this project?</i>

432
00:17:59,128 --> 00:18:00,194
I do.

433
00:18:01,297 --> 00:18:02,863
<i>No.</i>

434
00:18:02,931 --> 00:18:04,282
"No," what?

435
00:18:04,350 --> 00:18:07,618
<i>Judging by these results,
I'd say you are depressed,</i>

436
00:18:07,686 --> 00:18:09,297
<i>and I would turn you
away from the study.</i>

437
00:18:09,321 --> 00:18:10,721
I'm not depressed.

438
00:18:10,790 --> 00:18:12,034
<i>Oh, it's no big deal. We can get</i>

439
00:18:12,058 --> 00:18:13,402
<i>somebody else to
give us a baseline...</i>

440
00:18:13,426 --> 00:18:15,666
Derek, I'm not depressed.
Show me the kitten.

441
00:18:19,365 --> 00:18:21,032
Yeah. See?

442
00:18:21,100 --> 00:18:22,366
I'm happy.

443
00:18:23,669 --> 00:18:25,119
<i>Am I happy?</i>

444
00:18:25,188 --> 00:18:26,286
<i>Nope.</i>

445
00:18:26,355 --> 00:18:27,438
Well...

446
00:18:28,290 --> 00:18:29,407
Okay, well...

447
00:18:29,475 --> 00:18:31,242
No! Why are you...

448
00:18:32,378 --> 00:18:34,045
I really do love kittens.

449
00:18:34,113 --> 00:18:35,462
I do.

450
00:18:35,531 --> 00:18:37,309
Hey, Dr. Torres said you
have a thing for bones.

451
00:18:37,333 --> 00:18:39,100
When you're done
with her patient,

452
00:18:39,168 --> 00:18:40,879
you want to do a
mandibular ORIF?

453
00:18:40,903 --> 00:18:42,603
Yes!

454
00:18:42,671 --> 00:18:44,288
I see you have another beverage.

455
00:18:44,357 --> 00:18:45,817
Iced tea, actually.
It's quite good.

456
00:18:45,841 --> 00:18:46,961
Would you like some?

457
00:18:47,026 --> 00:18:48,592
Oh, I'm perfectly
happy with my water.

458
00:18:48,661 --> 00:18:50,077
Is that a...

459
00:18:50,146 --> 00:18:51,529
Her swimsuit. Yeah. Racerback.

460
00:18:51,597 --> 00:18:53,063
I ran out of underwear.

461
00:18:53,132 --> 00:18:54,648
I'm not understanding.

462
00:18:54,717 --> 00:18:56,312
You don't wear swimsuits when
you run out of clean underwear?

463
00:18:56,336 --> 00:18:57,813
I don't run out of
clean underwear.

464
00:18:57,837 --> 00:18:59,381
You're a resident. When do
you have time to do laundry?

465
00:18:59,405 --> 00:19:00,821
I'm a doctor. I send it out.

466
00:19:00,890 --> 00:19:01,906
Mmm.

467
00:19:04,844 --> 00:19:07,044
The incision looks good.

468
00:19:07,113 --> 00:19:08,546
Where are my parents?

469
00:19:08,615 --> 00:19:10,593
They went to check out
a support group we have

470
00:19:10,617 --> 00:19:12,282
for dealing with tough stuff.

471
00:19:12,351 --> 00:19:13,462
I'm the one who's stuck in here.

472
00:19:13,486 --> 00:19:14,685
You want to talk about it?

473
00:19:14,754 --> 00:19:15,920
No.

474
00:19:15,989 --> 00:19:17,488
Want to play checkers?

475
00:19:17,557 --> 00:19:19,056
No.

476
00:19:19,125 --> 00:19:20,224
Chess?

477
00:19:20,292 --> 00:19:21,626
No.

478
00:19:21,694 --> 00:19:24,562
Come on. You got to let
me beat you at something.

479
00:19:24,631 --> 00:19:26,964
I kind of feel like playing
with someone my own age.

480
00:19:28,568 --> 00:19:30,928
Whoa! Whoa! Careful. You're
gonna rip through the plastic.

481
00:19:32,772 --> 00:19:34,005
That's the point.

482
00:19:49,172 --> 00:19:51,289
Surgery's off. It's off?

483
00:19:51,357 --> 00:19:54,375
Donor backed out.

484
00:19:54,443 --> 00:19:57,344
Please tell Cristina
I'm thrilled for her.

485
00:19:57,413 --> 00:19:59,241
I'm sure she'd love
to hear it from you.

486
00:19:59,265 --> 00:20:00,775
And I would love to
have that conversation,

487
00:20:00,799 --> 00:20:02,944
but I am busy
trying to find a way

488
00:20:02,968 --> 00:20:06,270
for a gene to proliferate
in the body of a young boy.

489
00:20:06,339 --> 00:20:09,824
So, I would be most
grateful if you would extend

490
00:20:09,892 --> 00:20:13,443
my heartfelt congratulations
to Dr. Yang for me.

491
00:20:17,934 --> 00:20:19,366
Okay.

492
00:20:28,027 --> 00:20:29,460
You said he was stable.

493
00:20:29,529 --> 00:20:31,640
You said he had at least
one more week on ECMO.

494
00:20:31,664 --> 00:20:33,174
We thought that we
had it under control,

495
00:20:33,198 --> 00:20:34,710
and we didn't
expect for him to clot.

496
00:20:34,734 --> 00:20:37,434
And six months ago, I
didn't expect any of this.

497
00:20:37,503 --> 00:20:39,870
I was in a carpool
line picking up

498
00:20:39,939 --> 00:20:43,040
my three happy,
healthy kids from school.

499
00:20:44,276 --> 00:20:45,509
And now...

500
00:20:45,578 --> 00:20:48,446
Now I have two kids in
end-stage heart failure

501
00:20:48,514 --> 00:20:52,015
and one being kept
alive with a pacemaker.

502
00:20:52,084 --> 00:20:54,568
You guys can't tell me
why my kids are sick,

503
00:20:54,636 --> 00:20:56,614
and now you're
scratching your heads,

504
00:20:56,638 --> 00:20:59,417
telling me that there's nothing
more you can do for Link except...

505
00:20:59,441 --> 00:21:01,108
Except wait?

506
00:21:01,177 --> 00:21:03,539
I thought you were supposed to
be some award-winning doctor.

507
00:21:03,563 --> 00:21:04,763
Frankie.

508
00:21:04,797 --> 00:21:07,231
My parents keep saying
